Data science of climate change¶

Project by Gloria BENOIT, supervised by Pierre Poulain in Programmation Python 2 (BQAAY080, M1BI, 2023)¶

This project aims to quantify and characterize climate change, by finding data sources and reproducing scientific graphs. The project is being carried out in two stages: analysis of atmospheric CO2, followed by analysis of temperature trends.

Atmospheric CO2¶

Data source¶

National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)¶

NOAA is an agency of the U.S. department of commerce that “enriches life through science”. They work to keep the public informed of the changing environment around them. In 1972, they've created The Global Monitoring Laboratory (GML), as part of the NOAA Environmental Research Laboratories. It's mission is focused on geophysical monitoring for climatic change.

GML conducts research that addresses three major challenges: greenhouse gas and carbon cycle feedbacks, changes in clouds, aerosols, and surface radiation, and recovery of stratospheric ozone. One of four programs created by GML is the Carbon Cycle Greenhouse Gases (CCGG), in which the spatial and temporal distributions of greenhouse gases are measured and modeled.

The CCGG research area operates the Global Greenhouse Gas Reference Network, measuring the atmospheric distribution and trends of the three main long-term drivers of climate change, carbon dioxide (CO2), methane (CH4), and nitrous oxide (N2O), as well as carbon monoxide (CO) which is an important indicator of air pollution.

CO2 measurements in the 70s¶

NOAA Carbon Dioxide (CO2) measurements first began in 1967 at the Niwot Ridge high altitude research station, Colorado. Since then, the CCGG cooperative air sampling network measures CO2 from more than 50 sites world wide. In-Situ continuous measurements of CO2 at the NOAA GML Atmospheric Baseline Observatories began in 1973. Additional in-situ measurements from tall towers and light aircraft in the USA began in the 1990's, to support studies on continental sources and sinks of greenhouse gases. Vertical profile data from the AirCore Sampling System began in 2012 to monitor greenhouse gases at high altitudes and to help evaluate remote sensing measurements.

Flask (1968-2022)¶

GML measures greenhouse gases through a cooperative air sampling network effort which began in 1967. Air samples are collected approximately weekly with flasks from a globally distributed network of sites, ranging from being collected by volunteers to being collected by aircrafts.
Measurement data are used to identify long-term trends, seasonal variability, and spatial distribution of carbon cycle gases.

This data can be found in GML's CO2 database.

In situ (1973-2022)¶

Greenhouse gases are also measured at four Atmospheric Baseline Observatories and multiple tall towers in the United States. It first began measurements of CO2 at the observatories in 1973. Continuous in-situ measurements of these gases provides great detail in their long term trends, seasonal and short-term variations, and diurnal cycles.

This data can also be found in GML's CO2 database.

CO2 estimates before real measurements, paleoclimatology¶

The most direct method of investigating past variations of the atmospheric CO2 concentration before 1958, when continuous direct atmospheric CO2 measurements started, is the analysis of air extracted from suitable ice cores (Siegenthaler et al., 2005)

The measurement of the gas composition is direct: trapped in deep ice cores are tiny bubbles of ancient air, which we can extract and analyze using mass spectrometers.

From 1000 to 2004¶

In 2010, pre-industrial CO2 data was estimated using two ice cores. Measurements for Law Dome (LD) and Dronning Maud Land (DML) were sufficient to yield smoothed, with 50-year splines, estimates for CO2 evolution between 1000 and 2004 (Frank et al., 2010).

This data can be found in NOAA's Paleoclimatology database, as study 10437.

800,000 years before present¶

In 2008, two years prior, the Antarctic Vostok and EPICA Dome C ice cores had provided a composite record of atmospheric carbon dioxide levels over the past 800,000 years (Lüthi et al., 2008).

This data can also be found in NOAA's Paleoclimatology database, as study 6091.

Unit of measurement¶

When measuring gases the term concentration is used to describe the amount of gas by volume in the air. The two most common units of measurement are parts-per-million, and percent concentration. All of our data uses parts-per-million as their unit of measurement.
Parts-per-million (abbreviated ppm) is the ratio of one gas to another. For example, 1,000 ppm of CO2 means that if you could count a million gas molecules, 1,000 of them would be of carbon dioxide and 999,000 molecules would be some other gases.

In situ (1973-2022)¶

The dataset is stored in a text format, uses spaces as the separator and contains 20 columns for 593 lines. It contains a site code, which refers to the observatory where the data was recorded, the date, from the year down to the second, the CO2 record and other attributes of the measurements. Therefore, we have four different dataset, each specific to an observatory :

Barrow Mauna Loa American Samoa South Pole
BRW MLO SMO SPO

Their locations can be found directly on GML's site, where in situ observatories are marked by a blue rectangle.

In [4]:
def read_noaa_data(filename):
    """Read a dataframe from a NOAA file correctly.

    Parameters
    ----------
    filename : string
        A dataframe in a text file from NOAA.

    Returns
    -------
    dataframe :
        The dataframe.
    """
    df = pd.read_csv(filename, comment='#', sep=' ', header=0,
                     na_values=-999.99)
    df = df[["year", "month", "datetime", "time_decimal", "value"]]
    return df

In order to smooth the CO2 records, we also decided to add a rolling average of eleven adjacent seasonal cycles, centered on the month to be corrected. This number was chosen to center the average value over the year, erasing the seasonal variability. At any point in time, the CO2 recorded is adjusted by the values of the nearest four-season cycle.

In [5]:
def add_rollmean(df):
    """Add a rolling mean of 11 adjacent values to the value.

    Parameters
    ----------
    df : dataframe
        A dataframe containing a 'value' column.

    Returns
    -------
    dataframe :
        The dataframe with new 'rolling mean' column.
    """
    df["rolling_mean"] = df['value'].rolling(11, center=True).mean()
    return df

If we focus on the raw value, they are all very different depending on the observatory. However if we focus on the averaged value, we can assume they all increase in the same way. To make sure of this, we will calculate the slope of a linear least-squares regression fitted to each observatory, and compare the values obtained. From the multiple models, we can extrapolate the data to predict CO2 records up until 2050.

In [10]:
predictions = pd.DataFrame(list(range(2023, 2051)))
In [11]:
cpt = 0
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for obs_name in observatories:
    filename = f"co2_{obs_name}_surface-insitu_1_ccgg_MonthlyData.txt"
    df_noaa = read_noaa_data(filename)
    df_noaa = add_rollmean(df_noaa)
    df_noaa = df_noaa.dropna()
    res = stats.linregress(df_noaa["time_decimal"], df_noaa["rolling_mean"])
    plt.plot(df_noaa["time_decimal"],
             res.intercept + res.slope*df_noaa["time_decimal"],
             color=colors[cpt], label=(f"{observatories[obs_name]}, "
             f"a: {res.slope:.4f}"))
    plt.plot(predictions, res.intercept + res.slope*predictions,
             color="black", linestyle='--')
    cpt += 1
pred_leg = plt.plot([], [], label="Predictions for 2050", color="black",
                    linestyle='--')
plt.legend(loc="upper left")
plt.title("Linear regression on averaged CO2 record")
plt.show()

We can conclude that although the CO2 recorded seems vastly different depending on the observatory, it rises in the same way no matter where it's measured. However it may be possible that a linear least-squares regression isn't the best fit for our values. We will therefore try an exponential regression. We followed the following tutorial.

In [12]:
def exp_model(x, a, b):
    """Calculate an exponential regression.

    Parameters
    ----------
    x : float
        The predictor variable.
    a, b : float
        The regression coefficients that describe the relationship
        between x and y.
    Returns
    -------
    float :
        The response variable.
    """
    y = np.exp(a) * (np.exp(b) ** x)
    return y
In [13]:
cpt = 0
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
for obs_name in observatories:
    filename = f"co2_{obs_name}_surface-insitu_1_ccgg_MonthlyData.txt"
    df_noaa = read_noaa_data(filename)
    df_noaa = add_rollmean(df_noaa)
    df_noaa = df_noaa.dropna()
    fit = np.polyfit(df_noaa["time_decimal"],
                     np.log(df_noaa["rolling_mean"]), 1)
    plt.plot(df_noaa["time_decimal"], exp_model(df_noaa["time_decimal"],
             fit[1], fit[0]), color=colors[cpt],
             label=(f"{observatories[obs_name]}, "
             f"a: {fit[1]:.4f}, b: {fit[0]:.4f}"))
    plt.plot(predictions, exp_model(predictions, fit[1], fit[0]),
             color="black", linestyle='--')
    cpt += 1
pred_leg = plt.plot([], [], label="Predictions for 2050", color="black",
                    linestyle='--')
plt.legend(loc="upper left")
plt.title("Exponential regression on averaged CO2 record")
plt.show()

If CO2 records fit an exponential regression rather than a linear regression, atmospheric CO2 will increase quicker. For instance, we barely exceed 460ppm by 2050 using a linear regression, but we almost reach 480ppm using an exponential one.

Paleoclimatology¶

From the year 1000 to 2004¶

The dataset is also stored in a text format, but uses tabulations as the separator and contains 23 columns for 1005 lines. It contains the year of recording, from 1000 to 2004, and three mains values : the record at Law Dome (LD), the record at Dronning Maud Land (DML) and the average record over thoses two sites. Each of theses values is smoothed with splines ranging from 50 to 200 years with a 25 year step.

Temperature anomalies¶

The evolution of the world's climate is not measured and rendered using actual temperature values, but rather temperature anomalies. Scientists combine measurements from the air above land and the ocean surface, and this measure is compared daily to what is 'normal' for that location and time, typically the long-term average over a 30-year period. These anomalies are the temperature differences observed.

To take account of the diversity of the world's regions, temperatures are measured on a special global grid where each box is usually 5° by 5°. Global yearly temperature anomalies are an average of each annual grid value.

Data source¶

Scientists use four major datasets to study global temperature:

  • GISTEMP, by the NASA Goddard Institute for Space Sciences (GISS)
  • HadCRUT5, by the UK Met Office Hadley Centre and the University of East Anglia’s Climatic Research Unit
  • NOAAGlobalTemp (formely know as MLOST), by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA)
  • JMA, by the Japan Meteorological Agency

GISTEMP¶

The GISS Surface Temperature Analysis (GISTEMP) is an estimate of global surface temperature change. Measures date back to 1880 up until now, and temperature anomalies are deviations from the corresponding 1951-1980 means. Data combines land-surface air and sea-surface water temperature anomalies using files from NOAA GHCN v4 (meteorological stations) and ERSST v5 (ocean areas).

Data are plain-text files in tabular format of temperature anomalies (txt or csv). Users interested in the entire gridded surface air temperature anomaly data may download netCDF files containing selected series on a regular 2°×2° grid or the basic SBBX binary files.

HadCRUT5¶

HadCRUT5 is a gridded dataset of global historical surface temperature anomalies relative to a 1961-1990 reference period. Data are available for each month from January 1850 onwards, on a 5 degree grid and as global and regional average time series. The gridded data are a blend of the CRUTEM5 land-surface air temperature dataset and the HadSST4 sea-surface temperature (SST) dataset.

Time series data are provided in CSV and NetCDF formats.

NOAAGlobalTemp¶

The NOAA Merged Land Ocean Global Surface Temperature Analysis (NOAAGlobalTemp) combines long-term sea surface (water) temperature (SST) and land surface (air) temperature datasets to create a complete, accurate depiction of global temperature trends. The dataset is used to support climate monitoring activities such as the Monthly Global Climate Assessment, and also provides input data for a number of climate models.

Data is available as a series of temperature anomalies relative to a 1971–2000 monthly climatology. Monthly and annual land–ocean temperature time series as well as land-only and ocean-only time series are available from 1850 to present for several zonal bands.

Global Gridded 5° Monthly data are available in netCDF format.

JMA¶

JMA estimates global temperature anomalies using data combined not only over land but also over ocean areas in each 5° x 5° grid box worldwide. Temperature anomalies are measured from the 1991-2020 baseline since 1891.

Data are stored in ASCII.

Temperature estimates before real measurements, paleoclimatology¶

Past temperatures are measured using natural archives such as ice, rocks and fossils. However, temperature is not measured directly, but is instead inferred from special chemical properties, like the isotopic composition of the water molecules released by melting the ice cores.

We will be using the data computed by Osman et al., in 2021.

Unit of measurement¶

Daily anomalies are averaged together over a whole month. These are, in turn, used to work out temperature anomalies from season-to-season and year-to-year. A 'positive' anomaly means the temperature is warmer than the long-term average, whereas a 'negative' anomaly means it’s cooler. All anomalies are measured using degree Celsius (°C).

GISTEMP (1880-2022)¶

The dataset containing zonal annual means of combined Land-Surface Air and Sea-Surface Water temperature anomalies is available as a csv. It contains 15 columns for 143 lines, corresponding to the years between 1850 and 2022. The baseline used to convert temperature into anomalies is 1951-1980. Anomalies are listed for different zones, the distinctions of which are documented in Hansen et al. (2006). Here, only global temperature anomalies are of interest.

def showyourstripes(ax, anomaly, year, start_average, end_average, title=True):
    """Display temperature anomalies as stripes.

    Parameters
    ----------
    ax : matplotlib.axes._axes.Axes
        The axes on which to plot the stripes.
    anomaly : vector
        Temperature anomalies.
    year : vector
        Years of measures.
    start_average : int
        Beginning year of the reference period.
    end_average : int
        Last year of the reference period.
    """
    # Creating the gradient
    cmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('custom_colormap',
                                             ['#08306B', '#4292C6',
                                              '#C6DBEF', 'white',
                                              '#FB6A4A', '#EF3B2C',
                                              '#67000D'], N=len(anomaly))
    normalized = ((np.array(anomaly) - min(anomaly)) /
                  (max(anomaly) - min(anomaly)))
    colors = cmap(normalized)

    # Stripes plot
    ax.bar(year, [1] * len(year), color=colors, width=1)

    # Legends
    ax.set_facecolor('black')
    ax.set_xlim([min(year), max(year)])
    ax.set_ylim([0, 1])
    ax.yaxis.set_visible(False)
    if (title):
        ax.set_title("Relative to average of "
                     f"{start_average}-{end_average} (°C)", fontsize=10)
        ax.set_title(f"Global temperature change ({min(year)}-{max(year)})")
In [30]:
def showyourbars(ax, anomaly, year, start_average, end_average, title=True):
    """Display temperature anomalies as bars.

    Parameters
    ----------
    ax : matplotlib.axes._axes.Axes
        The axes on which to plot the bars.
    anomaly : vector
        Temperature anomalies.
    year : vector
        Years of measures.
    start_average : int
        Beginning year of the reference period.
    end_average : int
        Last year of the reference period.
    """
    # Creating the gradient
    cmap = LinearSegmentedColormap.from_list('custom_colormap',
                                             ['#08306B', '#4292C6',
                                              '#C6DBEF', 'white',
                                              '#FB6A4A', '#EF3B2C',
                                              '#67000D'], N=len(anomaly))
    normalized = ((np.array(anomaly) - min(anomaly)) /
                  (max(anomaly) - min(anomaly)))
    colors = cmap(normalized)

    # Bar plot
    ax.bar(year, anomaly, color=colors, width=1)

    # Legends
    ax.set_facecolor('black')
    ax.set_xlim([min(year), max(year)])
    ax.set_ylim([min(anomaly), max(anomaly)])
    if (title):
        ax.set_title("Relative to average of "
                     f"{start_average}-{end_average} (°C)", fontsize=10)
        ax.set_title(f"Global temperature change ({min(year)}-{max(year)})")
In [31]:
def showtempanalysis(name, anomaly, year, start_average, end_average):
    """Display temperature anomalies analysis.

    Shows both bars and stripes for the data.

    Parameters
    ----------
    name : string
        Name of the measurement technique.
    anomaly : vector
        Temperature anomalies.
    year : vector
        Years of measures.
    start_average : int
        Beginning year of the reference period.
    end_average : int
        Last year of the reference period.
    """
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(16, 6))
    showyourbars(ax[0], anomaly, year, start_average, end_average, title=False)
    showyourstripes(ax[1], anomaly, year,
                    start_average, end_average, title=False)
    fig.suptitle(f"{name} - Global temperature change "
                 f"({min(year)}-{max(year)})\nRelative to average of "
                 f"{start_average}-{end_average} (°C)", fontsize=15)
    plt.show()

HadCRUT5 (1850-2023)¶

Time series data are provided in CSV (comma-separated values). This specific dataset contains 4 columns and 174 lines, corresponding to the years between 1850 and 2023. Here we want to focus on the two first columns : the year and the global temperature anomaly observed. Temperature anomalies are computed as the difference between the means of regional time series computed for each of the 200 ensemble member realisations and the baseline of 1961-1990.

NOAAGlobalTemp (1850-2023)¶

Global Gridded 5° Monthly temperature anomalies are available in netCDF format, which is a file format for storing multidimensional scientific data, using 1971-2000 as the baseline. Here, we only want data displayed through time. We can therefore convert the data into a dataframe.

JMA (1891-2022)¶

Annual anomalies of the JMA's Global Surface Temperature are an average of monthly values, by the same 5° x 5° grid boxes as usual, compared to the 1991-2020 baseline. The complete annual dataset contains 36x72 values, corresponding to each grid boxes, by year. This means that the file contains 4752 rows, 36 for each year between 1891 and 2022, and 72 columns.
We will therefore assume that the averaged global value for each year is the average of the 36x72 values.

Paleoclimatology¶

The data is downloadable as an excel file, which contains both the data from the study and the one from the study by Tardif et al. in 2019. However, reading the file as an excel returns only the data from this study, which is what we want. For every 200 years BP, we have the estimated values for each percentile.

The value is the global mean surface temperature (GMST) estimate spanning the deglacial and Holocene periods using ~80 marine and terrestrial temperature proxies (Shakun et al. and Marcott et al.) compared to the preindustrial last millennium average (1000–1850 CE). To show the averaged value, we will focus on the estimated values for the 50th percentile.

Since values are estimated over 200 years, we will consider the first value of the interval as the true age. This age is BP, before present, meaning before 1950. Therefore, 0 BP actually means 1950. This has to be taken into account in order for the data to be displayed correctly.

Data confirmation¶

True global temperature values are hard to find online, but I've managed to find U.S. average temperatures between 1895 and 2023 for every month. Here we chose temperatures measured in May. Temperatures are given in Fahrenheit, with missing values being -99. We will need to take all of this into account to display the data correctly.

Using this data, we can compute the average temperature for the same baselines as the previous datasets, and compare them. As a reminder, HadCRUT5 used 1961-1990, GISTEMP used 1951-1980, NOAAGlobalTemp used 1971-2000 and JMA used 1991-2020.

In [57]:
df_compar = df_US[["Year", "Value"]]
# GISTEMP
baseline = df_compar.loc[(df_compar['Year'] >= 1951) &
                         (df_compar['Year'] <= 1980), 'Value'].mean()
df_compar["GISTEMP"] = df_compar["Value"] - baseline
# HadCRUT5
baseline = df_compar.loc[(df_compar['Year'] >= 1961) &
                         (df_compar['Year'] <= 1990), 'Value'].mean()
df_compar["HadCRUT5"] = df_compar["Value"] - baseline
# NOAAGlobalTemp
baseline = df_compar.loc[(df_compar['Year'] >= 1971) &
                         (df_compar['Year'] <= 2000), 'Value'].mean()
df_compar["NOAAGlobalTemp"] = df_compar["Value"] - baseline
# JMA
baseline = df_compar.loc[(df_compar['Year'] >= 1991) &
                         (df_compar['Year'] <= 2020), 'Value'].mean()
df_compar["JMA"] = df_compar["Value"] - baseline

Larger temperature anomalies are observed with the U.S. dataset, although it seems to evolve in the same way. This can be explained by the way temperatures were measured. Here, the temperature measured is that of the atmosphere, whereas the other datasets measure both land and sea surface.

To compare their evolution, we can use a rolling mean to smooth the U.S. data. We have arbitrarily chosen to average over 20 years, which visually yields a good fit.

In [59]:
df_compar_smooth = pd.DataFrame(df_compar["Year"])
smoothing = 20
for name in names:
    df_compar_smooth[name] = df_compar[name].rolling(smoothing,
                                                     center=True).mean()

Thus, we can confirm that the four datasets accurately compute temperature anomalies. In spite of baselines being different, all datasets show the same temperature trend.

Conclusion¶

We've proved that atmospheric CO2 records have been soaring since pre-industrial times (circa 1850), and that temperatures are also rising over time.
